dbr:Antwerp_Mannerism	rdfs:label	"Antwerpener Manieristen"@de ,
		"Manierismo de Amberes"@es ,
		"Mani\\u00E9risme anversois"@fr ,
		"Antwerp Mannerism"@en ;
	rdfs:comment	"Antwerp Mannerism is the name given to the style of a largely anonymous group of painters from Antwerp in the beginning of the 16th century.  The style bore no direct relation to Renaissance or Italian Mannerism, but the name suggests a peculiarity that was a reaction to the \\"classic\\" style of the earlier Flemish painters. Although attempts have been made to identify the individual artists, most of the paintings remain attributed to anonymous masters."@en ,
		"Le mani\\u00E9risme anversois se rapporte au style d\'un groupe de peintres travaillant \\u00E0 Anvers au d\\u00E9but du XVIe si\\u00E8cle. Le style n\'est pas en relation directe avec l\'art de la Renaissance italienne, mais sugg\\u00E8re une r\\u00E9action au style classique de la peinture flamande du XVe si\\u00E8cle.Bien que certaines tentatives d\'identification de personnalit\\u00E9s artistiques ind\\u00E9pendantes ont \\u00E9t\\u00E9 avanc\\u00E9es, ces peintures restent pour la plupart attribu\\u00E9es \\u00E0 des ma\\u00EEtres \\u00E0 nom de convention."@fr ,
		"El manierismo de Amberes es el nombre que se da al estilo de un amplio grupo de pintores, en gran medida an\\u00F3nimos, de Amberes a comienzos del siglo XVI. El estilo no ten\\u00EDa relaci\\u00F3n directa con el Renacimiento o el Manierismo italiano, pero el nombre sugiere una peculiaridad que era una reacci\\u00F3n al estilo \\u00ABcl\\u00E1sico\\u00BB de los pintores flamencos primitivos. Aunque se han hecho intentos de identificar artistas individuales, la mayor parte de las pinturas siguen atribuy\\u00E9ndose a maestros an\\u00F3nimos."@es ,
		"Die Gruppe der Antwerpener Manieristen umfasst eine nicht n\\u00E4her zu definierende Anzahl von Malern der Antwerpener St.-Lukas-Gilde zum Beginn des 16. Jahrhunderts."@de .

\\u66FF\\u308F\\u3063\\u305F\\u3002"@ja ,
		"Wu or Wumen School (Chinese: \\u5434\\u95E8\\u753B\\u6D3E) is the term applied to a group of painters of the Southern School during the Ming period of Chinese history. It was not an academy or educational institution, but rather a group united largely by the artistic theories of its members.  Often classified as Literati, scholars, or amateur painters (as opposed to professionals), members idealized the concepts of personalizing works and integrating the artists into the art."@en ,

		"Papunya Tula est un mouvement de la peinture aborig\\u00E8ne australienne n\\u00E9 au d\\u00E9but des ann\\u00E9es 1970 \\u00E0 Alice Springs, dans le Territoire du Nord."@fr ,
		"Papunya Tula, or Papunya Tula Artists Pty Ltd, is an artist cooperative formed in 1972 that is owned and operated by Aboriginal people from the Western Desert of Australia. The group is known for its innovative work with the Western Desert Art Movement, popularly referred to as \\"dot painting\\".  Credited with bringing Aboriginal art to world attention, its artists inspired many other Australian Aboriginal artists and styles."@en .
dbr:Regina_Five	rdfs:label	"Regina Five"@en ;
	rdfs:comment	"Regina Five is the name given to five abstract painters, Kenneth Lochhead, Arthur McKay, Douglas Morton, Ted Godwin, and Ronald Bloore, who displayed their works in the 1961 National Gallery of Canada\'s exhibition \\"Five Painters from Regina\\"."@en .
dbr:Soviet_dissidents	rdfs:label	"Soviet dissidents"@en ,
		"\\u0414\\u0438\\u0441\\u0441\\u0438\\u0434\\u0435\\u043D\\u0442\\u044B \\u0432 \\u0421\\u0421\\u0421\\u0420"@ru ,
		"Dissidenza in Unione Sovietica"@it ,
		"Radzieccy dysydenci"@pl ,
		"Disidentes sovi\\u00E9ticos"@es ;
	rdfs:comment	"Soviet dissidents were persons who disagreed with certain features in the embodiment of Soviet ideology and who were willing to speak out against them. The dissidents were small groups of marginalized intellectuals whose modest challenges to the Soviet regime met protection and encouragement from correspondents.In the 1950s, Soviet dissidents started leaking criticism to the West by sending documents and statements to foreign diplomatic missions in Moscow."@en ,

		"Los disidentes sovi\\u00E9ticos eran aquellos ciudadanos o grupos de la Uni\\u00F3n Sovi\\u00E9tica que estaban en desacuerdo con las pol\\u00EDticas y acciones de su gobierno y protestaron activamente contra ellas a trav\\u00E9s de medios no violentos. A trav\\u00E9s de estas protestas, las personas implicadas en dichas actividades sufrir\\u00EDan represalias tales como el hostigamiento, la persecuci\\u00F3n o finalmente el encarcelamiento, frecuentemente a manos de la NKVD o la KGB."@es ,
		"Per dissidenza in Unione Sovietica si intende l\'insieme di coloro che erano in disaccordo con le decisioni politiche nel periodo dell\'Unione Sovietica esistito dal 1917 al 1991."@it ,

dbr:Abstractionism	rdfs:label	"Abstractionism"@en ;
	rdfs:comment	"Abstractionism is the theory that the mind obtains some or all of its concepts by abstracting them from concepts it already has, or from experience. One may, for example, abstract \'green\' from a set of experiences which involve green along with other properties. Also, for example, one may abstract a generic concept like \'vegetable\' from the already possessed concepts of its instances (carrot, broccoli, onion, etc.). This view was criticized by George Berkeley and Peter Geach."@en .

		dbr:Tonalism .
dbr:Intimism	rdfs:label	"Intimism"@en ;
	rdfs:comment	"Intimism (Slovene: intimizem) was a poetic movement that emerged in Slovenia in 1945, after the end of World War II. Its main themes were love, disappointment and suffering and the projection of poet\'s inner feelings onto nature. Its beginner was Ivan Minatti, who was followed by Lojze Krakar.The climax of Intimism was achieved in 1953 with a collection of poetry titled Poems of the Four (Pesmi \\u0161tirih), co-authored by Janez Menart, Ciril Zlobec, Kajetan Kovi\\u010D and Tone Pav\\u010Dek."@en .

dbr:Social_sculpture	rdfs:label	"Soziale Plastik"@de ,
		"\\u30BD\\u30FC\\u30B7\\u30E3\\u30EB\\u30FB\\u30B9\\u30AB\\u30EB\\u30D7\\u30C1\\u30E3\\u30FC"@ja ,
		"Social sculpture"@en ;
	rdfs:comment	"Die Soziale Plastik, auch genannt die soziale Skulptur, ist eine spezifische Definition eines erweiterten Kunstbegriffs des deutschen K\\u00FCnstlers Joseph Beuys. Beuys nutzte die Begriffe, um damit seine Vorstellung einer gesellschaftsver\\u00E4ndernden Kunst zu erl\\u00E4utern."@de ,
		"Social sculpture is a specific example of the extended concept of art that was advocated by the conceptual artist and politician Joseph Beuys. Beuys created the term Social Sculpture to illustrate his idea of art\'s potential to transform society. As an artwork, a social sculpture includes human activity that strives to structure and shape society or the environment. The central idea of a social sculptor is an artist who creates structures in society using language, thought, action, and object."@en ,

		"Rafa\\u00EBl (Urbino, 6 april 1483 \\u2013 Rome, 6 april 1520) was een Italiaanse kunstenaar (voornamelijk kunstschilder) uit de hoogrenaissance.Rafa\\u00EBl is de naam waaronder hij nu wereldwijd bekend is. Zijn echte naam was Raffaello Sanzio. Hij is ook wel bekend onder namen als Raffaello Santi en Raffaello da Urbino. Zoals met vele kunstenaars uit de Italiaanse renaissance het geval is, wordt zijn leven beschreven in het beroemde boek Le Vite van de 16e-eeuwse schilder en schrijver Giorgio Vasari."@nl ,

De East Village ligt ten oosten van Greenwich Village en kreeg hierdoor zijn naam. 		"La East Village es un vecindario en la comuna de Manhattan, Nueva York.Este barrio est\\u00E1 rodeado por la calle 14 al norte, el r\\u00EDo East al este, la calle Houston al sur y la calle Bowery y la Tercera Avenida al oeste. Limita al oeste de Greenwich Village y el NoHo, al norte con Stuyvesant Town, y al sur con el Lower East Side. El barrio incluye el vecindario conocido como Alphabet City.La \\"East Village\\" fue, y para algunos a\\u00FAn es, parte del \\"Lower East Side\\"."@es ,
		"East Village ist ein Stadtteil im Bezirk Manhattan in New York. Es liegt \\u00F6stlich von Greenwich Village, s\\u00FCdlich von Gramercy und Stuyvesant Town, und n\\u00F6rdlich der Lower East Side. Innerhalb des Stadtteils liegen die Bowery, Alphabet City und Tompkins Square Park. Das Viertel war bis in die 1960er Jahre ein Teil der Lower East Side. Einst ein Mittelpunkt der New Yorker Subkultur, hat sich East Village zu einem popul\\u00E4ren Szeneviertel entwickelt."@de ,

Il est approximativement d\\u00E9limit\\u00E9 par la 14e rue au nord, par l\'East River \\u00E0 l\'est, Houston Street au sud et la 3e Avenue \\u00E0 l\'ouest. Il est situ\\u00E9 \\u00E0 l\'est de Greenwich Village, d\'o\\u00F9 son nom."@fr ,

	rdfs:comment	"Un nocturne \\u2014 \\u00E9tymologiquement, une \\u00AB musique pour la nuit \\u00BB \\u2014 est une forme musicale classique, reposant sur un mouvement lent, une expression path\\u00E9tique, divers ornements m\\u00E9lodiques et une partie centrale acc\\u00E9l\\u00E9r\\u00E9e. C\'est l\'une des expressions typiques du romantisme musical.Le nocturne se pr\\u00E9sente comme une pi\\u00E8ce confidentielle de courte dur\\u00E9e, que le compositeur irlandais John Field (1782-1837) fut l\'un des premiers \\u00E0 cultiver \\u00E0 partir de 1814."@fr ,

		"Um noturno \\u00E9 geralmente uma composi\\u00E7\\u00E3o musical que evoca, ou \\u00E9 inspirada pela noite. Foi cultivado durante o s\\u00E9culo XIX principalmente como uma pe\\u00E7a de car\\u00E1ter para piano solo, e sua origem \\u00E9 relacionada com o compositor irland\\u00EAs John Field. Entretanto, sua representa\\u00E7\\u00E3o mais conhecida se encontra nos 21 noturnos de Fr\\u00E9d\\u00E9ric Chopin. Ao final do s\\u00E9culo XVIII, cole\\u00E7\\u00F5es de pe\\u00E7as para conjunto de c\\u00E2mara eram intituladas de Notturno, uma vez que eram executadas \\u00E0 noite."@pt ,
		"El nocturno: Pieza de m\\u00FAsica vocal o instrumental, de melod\\u00EDa dulce y estructura libre.La denominaci\\u00F3n \\"nocturno\\" se le daba, en una primera instancia, en el siglo XVIII, a una pieza tocada a momentos, generalmente en fiestas de noche y despu\\u00E9s dejadas a un lado. Algunas veces llevaba consigo el equivalente italiano, notturno, con trabajos como el Notturno en D para cuatro orchestras, K.286, y la Serenata Notturna, K. 239, de Mozart."@es ,
		"Nokturn (w\\u0142. notturno, franc. nocturne, niem. W okresie klasycyzmu \\u2013 utw\\u00F3r wielocz\\u0119\\u015Bciowy o nieustalonej budowie, zbli\\u017Cony do divertimenta, serenady, cassation. W okresie romantyzmu \\u2013 utw\\u00F3r o charakterze miniatury instrumentalnej, g\\u0142\\u00F3wnie fortepianowej, najcz\\u0119\\u015Bciej w formie ABA, czasem w formie ronda (np. Nokturn g-moll op.37 F."@pl ,
		"A nocturne (from the French which meant nocturnal, from Latin nocturnus) is usually a musical composition that is inspired by, or evocative of, the night. Historically, nocturne is a very old term applied to night Offices and, since the Middle Ages, to divisions in the canonical hour of Matins."@en ,

		"Het muzikale genre van de nocturne werd door de Ierse componist John Field begin 19e eeuw ge\\u00EFntroduceerd. Een nocturne is een muzikale compositie, die voortvloeide uit de sfeer van de nacht, een zeer romantisch of dromerig geheel.Onder invloed van Field heeft Fr\\u00E9d\\u00E9ric Chopin deze vorm diverse malen gebruikt voor de piano. De bekendste nocturnes zijn van zijn hand. Andere componisten die nocturnes hebben geschreven, zijn onder andere Gabriel Faur\\u00E9, Claude Debussy en Erik Satie."@nl ,
		"Un notturno (dal francese nocturne) \\u00E8 una composizione musicale ispirata alla notte.La dicitura \\u00ABnotturno\\u00BB fu per la prima volta impiegata nel XVIII secolo, quando stava ad indicare un\'opera in vari movimenti.Accanto all\'equivalente in alcune lingue, talvolta troviamo anche il corrispettivo termine in italiano. Un esempio pu\\u00F2 essere rappresentato dalla celebre Eine kleine Nachtmusik di Mozart, la cui traduzione \\u00E8 \\u00ABPiccola serenata notturna\\u00BB."@it ,
		"Das (auch: \\u201Edie\\u201C) Nocturne bzw. Notturno (dt. wortw\\u00F6rtl.: \\u201ENacht werdend\\u201C, meist: \\u201En\\u00E4chtlich\\u201C) ist eine in der Zeit des Barock entstandene Form, die in ihrer Besetzung und Satzstruktur nicht festgelegt ist. In dieser Zeit \\u00FCberschneidet sich die Bezeichnung Nocturne mit der Serenade."@de .

		"L\'imagisme est un mouvement po\\u00E9tique anglo-am\\u00E9ricain du d\\u00E9but du XXe si\\u00E8cle qui souhaite s\'affranchir de la tradition po\\u00E9tique romantique et victorienne en choisissant un langage imag\\u00E9, une expression pr\\u00E9cise et directe. Les \\u00AB imagistes \\u00BB rejetaient l\'artifice typique de beaucoup de po\\u00E8tes romantiques de la p\\u00E9riode victorienne. Ils se situent en opposition aux po\\u00E8tes g\\u00E9orgiens beaucoup plus respectueux de la tradition."@fr ,
		"Imagizm (imaginizm) \\u2013 ruch poetycki w poezji angielskiej i ameryka\\u0144skiej w latach 1910-1918. 		"Imagisme is een po\\u00EBtische beweging die bloeide in de Verenigde Staten en Engeland tussen 1909 en 1917. De belangrijkste voorlopers van de imagisten waren de symbolisten, met name de groep Franse dichters in de jaren 1860 die zichzelf de parnassiens noemden."@nl ,
		"Em 1921, Pound lan\\u00E7ou em Londres uma escola est\\u00E9tica modernista, a qual chamou de Imagismo, em que defendia o uso da linguagem coloquial, a cria\\u00E7\\u00E3o de novos ritmos sonoros ultrapassando a m\\u00E9trica, liberdade na escolha do assunto, verso livre, poesia clara e apresenta\\u00E7\\u00E3o de imagens, procurando traduzir detalhes com precis\\u00E3o."@pt ,
		"Imagism was a movement in early 20th-century Anglo-American poetry that favored precision of imagery and clear, sharp language. It has been described as the most influential movement in English poetry since the activity of the Pre-Raphaelites. As a poetic style it gave Modernism its start in the early 20th century, and is considered to be the first organized Modernist literary movement in the English language."@en ,
		"No confundir con imaginismo, corriente literaria latinoamericana y rusaEl imagismo (del ingl\\u00E9s imagism) fue una corriente est\\u00E9tica literaria de la poes\\u00EDa angloamericana de comienzos del Siglo XX que favorec\\u00EDa la precisi\\u00F3n de la imagen (image en ingl\\u00E9s), y un lenguaje claro y preciso.Los imaginistas rechazaron el sentimiento y el artificio t\\u00EDpico de las l\\u00EDricas rom\\u00E1ntica y postrom\\u00E1ntica victoriana, en contra de sus contempor\\u00E1neos los poetas georgianos, que trabajaban dentro de la tradici\\u00F3n."@es ,
		"L\\u2019Imagismo \\u00E8 una corrente letteraria nata e diffusasi negli USA e nel Regno Unito nei primi anni del Novecento."@it .

		"El arte pop (Pop Art) fue un importante movimiento art\\u00EDstico del siglo XX que se caracteriza por el empleo de im\\u00E1genes de la cultura popular tomadas de los medios de comunicaci\\u00F3n, tales como anuncios publicitarios, comic books, objetos culturales \\u00ABmundanos\\u00BB y del mundo del cine."@es ,
		"Pop Art ist eine Kunstrichtung, vor allem in der Malerei und Skulptur, die Mitte der 1950er Jahre unabh\\u00E4ngig voneinander in England und den USA entstand, und in den 1960er Jahren zu einer vorherrschenden k\\u00FCnstlerischen Ausdrucksform Nordamerikas und Europas wurde. 		"Pop art is an art movement that emerged in the mid-1950s in Britain and in the late 1950s in the United States. Pop art presented a challenge to traditions of fine art by including imagery from popular culture such as advertising and news. In pop art, material is sometimes visually removed from its known context, isolated, and/or combined with unrelated material."@en ,

		"Pop art ou Arte pop \\u00E9 um movimento art\\u00EDstico surgido na d\\u00E9cada de 60 na Inglaterra mas que alcan\\u00E7ou sua maturidade na d\\u00E9cada de 80 em Nova York. 	rdfs:comment	"La Confraternita dei Preraffaelliti \\u00E8 stata una corrente artistica della pittura vittoriana (XIX secolo), nata nel settembre del 1848, sviluppatasi ed esauritasi in Gran Bretagna. Ascrivibile alla corrente del simbolismo, pu\\u00F2 essere definita - insieme al raffinato simbolismo di Klimt e alle forme del liberty - l\'unica trasposizione pittorica del decadentismo.La Confraternita si svilupp\\u00F2 durante l\'et\\u00E0 vittoriana, periodo particolarmente importante sia per la societ\\u00E0 che per le arti britanniche."@it ,
		"Die Pr\\u00E4raffaeliten waren eine in der Mitte des 19. Jahrhunderts in England zusammengekommene Gruppe von K\\u00FCnstlern. Diese pr\\u00E4gten den nach ihnen benannten Pr\\u00E4raffaelismus, einen Stil, der stark beeinflusst war von den Malern des italienischen Trecento und Quattrocento und von den deutschen Nazarenern \\u2013 aber auch von K\\u00FCnstlern der italienischen Renaissance wie Botticelli und insbesondere Raffael, obwohl die Pr\\u00E4raffaeliten jene bereits ablehnten."@de ,

		"The Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood (later known as the Pre-Raphaelites) was a group of English painters, poets, and critics, founded in 1848 by William Holman Hunt, John Everett Millais and Dante Gabriel Rossetti."@en ,
		"A Irmandade Pr\\u00E9-Rafaelita (Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood ou  PRB em ingl\\u00EAs), tamb\\u00E9m Fraternidade Pr\\u00E9-Rafaelita ou, simplesmente, Pr\\u00E9-Rafaelitas, foi um grupo art\\u00EDstico fundado em Inglaterra em 1848 por Dante Gabriel Rossetti, William Holman Hunt e John Everett Millais e dedicado principalmente \\u00E0 pintura. Este grupo, organizado ao modo de uma confraria medieval, surge como reac\\u00E7\\u00E3o \\u00E0 arte acad\\u00E9mica inglesa que seguia os moldes dos artistas cl\\u00E1ssicos do Renascimento."@pt ,
		"Le Pr\\u00E9rapha\\u00E9lisme est un mouvement artistique n\\u00E9 au Royaume-Uni en 1848. Ce mouvement tient la peinture des ma\\u00EEtres italiens du XVe si\\u00E8cle, pr\\u00E9d\\u00E9cesseurs de Rapha\\u00EBl, comme le mod\\u00E8le \\u00E0 imiter."@fr ,
		"De prerafa\\u00EBlieten waren Engelse kunstenaars in het Victoriaanse tijdperk, voornamelijk kunstschilders, die zich afzetten tegen de academische kunst als toen voorgeschreven door de Royal Academy of Arts. Prerafa\\u00EBlieten wilden terugkeren naar de eenvoud zoals die bestond bij kunstenaars levend v\\u00F3\\u00F3r Rafa\\u00EBl. Ze streefden eenvoudige composities en een nauwkeurige, realistische werkwijze na."@nl ,

		"Russische literatuur omvat alle in het Russisch geschreven teksten waaraan literaire waarde wordt toegekend. De Russisch literatuur kende een grote bloeiperiode in de 19e eeuw, met schrijvers als Poesjkin, Tolstoj, Dostojevski, Toergenjev en Tsjechov. Lange periodes, maar met name ook in het grootste deel van de twintigste eeuw, zwichtte de Russische literatuur sterk onder de censuur van het Russische staatsbewind."@nl ,
		"Con el t\\u00E9rmino literatura rusa se alude no solo a la literatura de Rusia, sino tambi\\u00E9n a la literatura escrita en ruso por miembros de otras naciones que se independizaron de la extinta Uni\\u00F3n de Rep\\u00FAblicas Socialistas Sovi\\u00E9ticas (URSS) o por emigrados que fueron acogidos en ella. Con la desintegraci\\u00F3n de la URSS varias culturas y pa\\u00EDses han reclamado a varios escritores exsovi\\u00E9ticos que, sin embargo, escrib\\u00EDan en ruso."@es ,

		"Los pintores de la Escuela de Siena o escuela sienesa durante los primeros a\\u00F1os del Trecento, mediante una metodolog\\u00EDa diferenciada de Giotto y de la escuela florentina, m\\u00E1s inspirada en los modelos y la t\\u00E9cnica a la maniera greca, tambi\\u00E9n lograron formular el tema del espacio pict\\u00F3rico.Una falta de preocupaci\\u00F3n por los problemas t\\u00E9cnicos o de proporciones que se manifest\\u00F3 en la estilizaci\\u00F3n y el amaneramiento de las figuras as\\u00ED como en el uso de los fondos ornamentales dorados y una gama de colores subjetiva, proporcionan una notable expresividad l\\u00EDrica a las composiciones que es el car\\u00E1cter propio de la pintura de la escuela sienesa. "@es ,
		"The Sienese School of painting flourished in Siena, Italy between the 13th and 15th centuries and for a time rivaled Florence, though it was more conservative, being inclined towards the decorative beauty and elegant grace of late Gothic art. Its most important representatives include Duccio, whose work shows Byzantine influence; his pupil Simone Martini; Pietro and Ambrogio Lorenzetti; Domenico and Taddeo di Bartolo; Sassetta and Matteo di Giovanni."@en ,
		"Szko\\u0142a siene\\u0144ska \\u2013 szko\\u0142a w\\u0142oskiego malarstwa maj\\u0105ca o\\u015Brodek w Sienie, rozwijaj\\u0105ca si\\u0119 mi\\u0119dzy XIII a XV wiekiem i przez pewien czas dor\\u00F3wnuj\\u0105ca \\u015Bwietno\\u015Bci\\u0105 szkole florenckiej.Przejawia\\u0142a wi\\u0119ksze przywi\\u0105zanie do tradycji oraz sk\\u0142onno\\u015B\\u0107 do dekoracyjno\\u015Bci i elegancji sztuki p\\u00F3\\u017Anego gotyku. Arty\\u015Bci ci tworzyli zar\\u00F3wno dzie\\u0142a o tematyce religijnej, jak i, co wa\\u017Cne, \\u015Bwieckiej, ukazuj\\u0105cej ludzi, krajobrazy, architektur\\u0119, prac\\u0119 i rozrywki."@pl ,
		"Die Schule von Siena war eine Malereibewegung in Siena (Italien) zwischen dem 13. und 15. Jahrhundert. In dieser Zeit war sie neben der Florentiner Malerei eine der bedeutendsten, wobei sie eine eher konservative Linie, gepr\\u00E4gt von der Gotik verfolgte. Unter den bekanntesten Vertretern waren Duccio, dessen Arbeiten einen byzantinischen Einfluss zeigten, und sein Sch\\u00FCler Simone Martini."@de ,
		"L\'\\u00E9cole siennoise de peinture en Italie s\'\\u00E9tend  du XIIIe au XVIe si\\u00E8cle et se d\\u00E9veloppe parall\\u00E8lement \\u00E0 l\'art pictural de l\'\\u00E9cole florentine, par un go\\u00FBt raffin\\u00E9 pour la couleur, h\\u00E9rit\\u00E9 de Byzance, avec un chromatisme tr\\u00E8s particulier, orang\\u00E9s, rouges tr\\u00E8s vifs, verts amandes et un jeu subtil d\'opposition des chauds et des froids."@fr ,

		"La scuola senese di pittura fior\\u00EC in Italia tra il XIII ed il XV secolo e riusc\\u00EC a competere con Firenze, nonostante fosse pi\\u00F9 conservativa e si focalizzasse maggiormente sulla bellezza decorativa e l\'eleganza dell\'ultimo periodo dell\'arte gotica.Tra i suoi rappresentanti pi\\u00F9 importanti troviamo Duccio di Buoninsegna, le cui opere mostrano una certa influenza bizantina, il suo apprendista Simone Martini, Pietro e Ambrogio Lorenzetti, Domenico e Taddeo di Bartolo, Stefano di Giovanni (il Sassetta) e Matteo di Giovanni.Nel XVI secolo ne fecero parte i manieristi Domenico di Pace Beccafumi e Giovanni Antonio Bazzi (il Sodoma)."@it .

		"Hyperrealisme"@nl ;
	rdfs:comment	"Hyperrealisme (ook: fotorealisme of superrealisme) is een stroming in de postmoderne schilderkunst en beeldhouwkunst uit de jaren 60 en 70 van de twintigste eeuw. In deze figuratieve stijl wordt de werkelijkheid op een zo realistisch en neutraal mogelijke manier weergegeven."@nl ,
		"Hiper-realismo \\u00E9 um g\\u00EAnero de pintura e escultura que tem um efeito semelhante ao da fotografia de alta resolu\\u00E7\\u00E3o. O hiper-realismo \\u00E9 uma evolu\\u00E7\\u00E3o do fotorrealismo, e o termo foi usado para designar um movimento art\\u00EDstico que nasceu nos Estados Unidos e na Europa em torno de 2000."@pt ,
		"El hiperrealismo es una tendencia radical de la pintura realista surgida en Estados Unidos a finales de los a\\u00F1os 1960 que propone reproducir la realidad con m\\u00E1s fidelidad y objetividad que la fotograf\\u00EDa. A veces se confunde con el fotorrealismo que es menos radical.El t\\u00E9rmino hiperrealismo es tambi\\u00E9n aplicable a la escultura y la historieta (Luis Garc\\u00EDa, Alex Ross, etc)."@es ,
		"L\'hyperr\\u00E9alisme est un mouvement/courant artistique am\\u00E9ricain des ann\\u00E9es 1950-1960. C\'est un r\\u00E9alisme quasiment photographique. Il s\'inspire d\'Edward Hopper et du Pop Art. Il est aussi nomm\\u00E9 aux \\u00C9tats-Unis photorealism ou superralism."@fr ,
		"Der Hyperrealismus, auch Superrealismus, ist eine Kunstrichtung, die Malerei und Skulptur, aber auch Fotografie und Film umfasst. Der Realismus war immer ein wichtiges Element in der Reihe der Stilrichtungen in der Kunst. Der Hyperrealismus ist eine Weiterentwicklung des Realismus und benachbart zur Pop Art."@de ,
		"L\'iperrealismo \\u00E8 un genere di pittura basato sulla riproduzione di un soggetto fotografico."@it ,
		"Hyperrealism is a genre of painting and sculpture resembling a high-resolution photograph.  Hyperrealism is considered an advancement of Photorealism by the methods used to create the resulting paintings or sculptures.  The term is primarily applied to an independent art movement and art style in the United States and Europe that has developed since the early 2000s."@en ,
		"\\u0413\\u0438\\u043F\\u0435\\u0440\\u0440\\u0435\\u0430\\u043B\\u0438\\u0437\\u043C \\u2014 \\u0442\\u0435\\u0440\\u043C\\u0438\\u043D, \\u043A\\u043E\\u0442\\u043E\\u0440\\u044B\\u0439 \\u0438\\u0441\\u043F\\u043E\\u043B\\u044C\\u0437\\u0443\\u0435\\u0442\\u0441\\u044F \\u0434\\u043B\\u044F \\u043E\\u0431\\u043E\\u0437\\u043D\\u0430\\u0447\\u0435\\u043D\\u0438\\u044F:\\u0430) \\u0442\\u0435\\u0447\\u0435\\u043D\\u0438\\u044F \\u0432 \\u0441\\u043E\\u0432\\u0440\\u0435\\u043C\\u0435\\u043D\\u043D\\u043E\\u043C \\u0438\\u0441\\u043A\\u0443\\u0441\\u0441\\u0442\\u0432\\u0435 (\\u0436\\u0438\\u0432\\u043E\\u043F\\u0438\\u0441\\u0438, \\u0441\\u043A\\u0443\\u043B\\u044C\\u043F\\u0442\\u0443\\u0440\\u0435 \\u0438 \\u043A\\u0438\\u043D\\u0435\\u043C\\u0430\\u0442\\u043E\\u0433\\u0440\\u0430\\u0444\\u0438\\u0438) 1990\\u20142000-\\u0445 \\u0433\\u043E\\u0434\\u043E\\u0432;\\u0431) \\u0442\\u0432\\u043E\\u0440\\u0447\\u0435\\u0441\\u0442\\u0432\\u0430 \\u0435\\u0432\\u0440\\u043E\\u043F\\u0435\\u0439\\u0441\\u043A\\u0438\\u0445 \\u0444\\u043E\\u0442\\u043E\\u0440\\u0435\\u0430\\u043B\\u0438\\u0441\\u0442\\u043E\\u0432 1970-\\u0445 \\u0433\\u043E\\u0434\\u043E\\u0432."@ru .

dbr:Greek_lyric	rdfs:label	"Lirica greca"@it ,
		"Greek lyric"@en ;
	rdfs:comment	"Greek lyric is the body of lyric poetry written in dialects of ancient Greek. It is primarily associated with the early 7th to the early 5th centuries BC, sometimes called the \\"Lyric Age of Greece\\", but continued to be written into the Hellenistic and Imperial periods. Lyric is one of three broad categories of poetry in classical antiquity, along with drama and epic, according to the scheme of the \\"natural forms of poetry\\" developed by Goethe in the early nineteenth century."@en ,
		"Nella Grecia antica, la lirica (o lyrica) era quel genere poetico che faceva ricorso al canto o  all\'accompagnamento di strumenti a corde come la lyra, differenziandosi in questo dalla poesia recitativa."@it .

dbr:Anti-establishment	rdfs:label	"Anti-establishment"@en ,
		"Anti-establishment"@pt ,
		"Antisyst\\u00E8me"@fr ,
		"Antisistema"@es ;
	rdfs:comment	"An anti-establishment view or belief is one which stands in opposition to the conventional social, political, and economic principles of a society. The term was first used in the modern sense in 1958, by the British magazine New Statesman to refer to its political and social agenda. The term can be distinguished from counterculture, a word normally used to describe artistic rather than political movements that run against the prevailing taste and values of the time."@en ,
		"Anti-establishment \\u00E9 um adjetivo da l\\u00EDngua inglesa usado para designar um indiv\\u00EDduo, grupo ou id\\u00E9ia que \\u00E9 contra as institui\\u00E7\\u00F5es oficiais, sejam elas pol\\u00EDticas, econ\\u00F4micas ou sociais, da forma vigente da sociedade. Em portugu\\u00EAs tamb\\u00E9m se usa a express\\u00E3o \\"contra a ordem estabelecida\\".== Refer\\u00EAncias =="@pt ,
		"Antisyst\\u00E8me est un adjectif qualifiant des personnes, des groupes ou des partis politiques portant un discours critiquant les institutions politiques dominantes.Giovanni Sartori a d\\u00E9fini parti anti-syst\\u00E8me en 1976 comme un parti qui  en proposant dans leur programme une alternative cr\\u00E9dible, suscitant un app\\u00E9tit de changement chez les \\u00E9lecteurs et produisant des conflits entre les partis conventionnels."@fr ,
		"Antisistema (o movimiento antisistema, o grupo antisistema, o contra-poder) se refiere a aquella persona o grupo de personas con una ideolog\\u00EDa disconforme con el orden pol\\u00EDtico o social establecido, que mediante reivindicaciones o acciones tratan de cambiar el statu quo."@es .

dbr:Xungen_movement	rdfs:label	"\\u5BFB\\u6839\\u6587\\u5B66"@zh ,
		"Xungen-Literatur"@de ,
		"Xungen movement"@en ,
		"Qu\\u00EAte des racines"@fr ,
		"Xungen wenxue"@pl ;
	rdfs:comment	"Le mouvement de la \\u00AB Qu\\u00EAte des racines \\u00BB (ou \\u00AB Recherche des racines \\u00BB ; chinois \\u5BFB\\u6839\\u6587\\u5B66), xungen wenxue, est un mouvement litt\\u00E9raire chinois contemporain.Le mouvement est n\\u00E9 en 1985 autour des \\u00E9crivains Han Shaogong (en), A Cheng, Zheng Wanlong (1944-) et Li Hangyu (1959-). L\'inspirateur du mouvement est l\'\\u00E9crivain Wang Zengqi (en) (1920-1997), qui \\u00E0 partir du d\\u00E9but des ann\\u00E9es 1980, \\u00E9crit des r\\u00E9cits, transpos\\u00E9s dans les ann\\u00E9es 1930, ayant pour cadre Gaoyou, dans sa province natale, le Jiangsu."@fr ,
		"Xungen wenxue (chin. \\u5BFB\\u6839\\u6587\\u5B66; literatura poszukiwania korzeni) - nurt wsp\\u00F3\\u0142czesnej literatury chi\\u0144skiej zapocz\\u0105tkowany przez prozatorsk\\u0105 grup\\u0119 literack\\u0105 xungen pai (grupa poszukiwania korzeni), powsta\\u0142\\u0105 na konferencji pisarzy i krytyk\\u00F3w XII 1984 w Hangzhou, dzia\\u0142aj\\u0105c\\u0105 do 1988."@pl ,
		"Xungen-Literatur (chinesisch \\u5C0B\\u6839\\u6587\\u5B78 / \\u5BFB\\u6839\\u6587\\u5B66, Pinyin x\\u00FAng\\u0113n w\\u00E9nxu\\u00E9), auch bekannt als Wurzelliteratur oder Literatur der Wurzelsuche, ist eine Literaturstr\\u00F6mung, die in der Volksrepublik China in der 2. H\\u00E4lfte der 1980er-Jahre aufkam. Die Wurzeln der chinesischen Zivilisation wurden im Bauerntum gesucht und anhand neuer Methoden analysiert. Diese retrospektive Literaturstr\\u00F6mung durchbrach den offiziell sanktionierten Realismus und die g\\u00E4ngige politische Rhetorik."@de ,
		"The xungen movement is a cultural and literary movement in mainland China emphasizing local and minority cultures. It began in the late-1980s. Its premise is that the Cultural Revolution damaged a pluralistic Chinese identity that had existed for centuries, and that the reconstruction of that identity requires a healthy appreciation of local cultures."@en .

		"El brutalismo es un estilo arquitect\\u00F3nico que surgi\\u00F3 del Movimiento Moderno y que tuvo su auge entre las d\\u00E9cadas de 1950 y 1970. En sus principios estaba inspirado por el trabajo del arquitecto suizo Le Corbusier (en particular en su edificio Unit\\u00E9 d\'Habitation) y en Eero Saarinen. El t\\u00E9rmino tiene su origen en el t\\u00E9rmino franc\\u00E9s b\\u00E9ton brut u \'hormig\\u00F3n crudo\', un t\\u00E9rmino usado por Le Corbusier para describir su elecci\\u00F3n de los materiales."@es ,

		"Brutalizm \\u2013 nurt architektury p\\u00F3\\u017Anego modernizmu powsta\\u0142y w ko\\u0144cu lat 40. XX wieku. Brutalizm zak\\u0142ada\\u0142 \\u017Ce najwa\\u017Cniejsze s\\u0105: przestrze\\u0144, konstrukcja i uwra\\u017Cliwienie na w\\u0142a\\u015Bciwo\\u015Bci zastosowanych materia\\u0142\\u00F3w. 		"A arquitectura brutalista foi um movimento arquitet\\u00F4nico desenvolvido por arquitetos modernos em meados das d\\u00E9cadas de 50 e 60. O brutalismo desenvolveu-se a partir de uma radicaliza\\u00E7\\u00E3o de determinados preceitos modernos."@pt ,
		"Brutalist architecture is a movement in architecture that flourished from the 1950s to the mid-1970s, descending from the modernist architectural movement of the early 20th century. The term originates from the French word for \\"raw\\" in the term used by Le Corbusier to describe his choice of material b\\u00E9ton brut (raw concrete)."@en ,
		"Brutalisme is een stroming binnen de architectuur die is ontstaan vanuit het modernisme. Het brutalisme kende zijn hoogtijperiode in de jaren 50 tot en met de jaren 70.Aanvankelijk werd het brutalisme vooral ge\\u00EFnspireerd door de Zwitserse architect Le Corbusier (vooral in zijn Unit\\u00E9 d\'Habitation gebouw) en door Ludwig Mies van der Rohe. De term brutalisme is afgeleid van het Franse b\\u00E9ton brut, of \\"ruw beton\\". Kenmerkend voor de stijl zijn blok-achtige, geometrische en herhalende vormen."@nl ,
		"Le brutalisme d\\u00E9signe un style architectural d\'origine anglo-saxonne qui est issu du modernisme. Il connut une grande consid\\u00E9ration entre les ann\\u00E9es 1950 et 1970. Puis il condensa sur lui une grande impopularit\\u00E9 : c\'est sous ce nom que l\'on rassembla toutes les constructions dures et imposantes en b\\u00E9ton."@fr .

	rdfs:comment	"The cinema of the United States, often generally referred to as Hollywood, has had a profound effect on cinema across the world since the early 20th century. Its history is sometimes separated into four main periods: the silent film era, classical Hollywood cinema, New Hollywood, and the contemporary period. While the French Lumi\\u00E8re Brothers are generally credited with the birth of modern cinema, it is American cinema that soon became the most dominant force in an emerging industry."@en ,

		"L\'histoire de la po\\u00E9sie des \\u00C9tats-Unis est profond\\u00E9ment li\\u00E9e \\u00E0 l\'histoire de la nation am\\u00E9ricaine elle-m\\u00EAme, ses conflits, ses guerres, et de ses \\u00E9volutions \\u00E9conomiques et sociales. La po\\u00E9sie am\\u00E9ricaine \\u00E9merge v\\u00E9ritablement dans la litt\\u00E9rature de langue anglaise durant l\'\\u00E9poque coloniale, lorsque les \\u00C9tats-Unis sont encore des territoires britanniques."@fr ,
		"American poetry, the poetry of the United States, arose first as efforts by colonists to add their voices to English poetry in the 17th century, well before the constitutional unification of the thirteen colonies (although before this unification, a strong oral tradition often likened to poetry existed among Native American societies). Unsurprisingly, most of the early colonists\' work relied on contemporary British models of poetic form, diction, and theme."@en ,
		"La Poes\\u00EDa de Estados Unidos (conocida en el \\u00E1mbito anglosaj\\u00F3n por el nombre de \\u00ABAmerican Poetry\\u00BB) comenz\\u00F3 con los primeros intentos de los colonos de sumar sus voces a la de la poes\\u00EDa inglesa del siglo XVII, bastante antes de que las Trece Colonias se unificasen constitucionalmente (previamente, una importante tradici\\u00F3n oral ligada a lo po\\u00E9tico existi\\u00F3 en las sociedades de los pueblos nativos de la zona)."@es ,

	rdfs:comment	"Literatura \\u00E1rabe (em \\u00E1rabe: \\u0627\\u0644\\u0623\\u062F\\u0628 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0639\\u0631\\u0628\\u064A, transl. Al-Adab Al-Arabi) \\u00E9 o nome dado a toda a obra escrita produzida, tanto em prosa quanto poesia, pelos falantes - n\\u00E3o necessariamente nativos - do idioma \\u00E1rabe. Normalmente n\\u00E3o inclui obras escritas no alfabeto \\u00E1rabe por\\u00E9m em outros idiomas, como o persa e o urdu."@pt ,
		"Arabic literature (Arabic: \\u0627\\u0644\\u0623\\u062F\\u0628 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0639\\u0631\\u0628\\u064A\\u200E / ALA-LC: al-Adab al-\\u2018Arab\\u012B) is the writing, both prose and poetry, produced by writers in the Arabic language. The Arabic word used for literature is \\"Adab\\", which is derived from a meaning of etiquette, and which implies politeness, culture and enrichment.Arabic literature emerged in the 5th century with only fragments of the written language appearing before then."@en ,
		"\\u0410\\u0440\\u0430\\u0431\\u0441\\u043A\\u0430\\u044F \\u043B\\u0438\\u0442\\u0435\\u0440\\u0430\\u0442\\u0443\\u0440\\u0430"@ru ,
		"Arabische Literatur im engeren Sinn ist Literatur in arabischer Sprache. Im weiteren Sinn versteht man darunter auch Literatur von arabischen Autoren, in welcher Sprache auch immer das Original verfasst wurde. Zum einen schreiben etliche bedeutende arabische Autoren in anderen Sprachen als Arabisch, sei es, dass sie die Sprache des ehemaligen Koloniallandes benutzen, wie es im Maghreb h\\u00E4ufig vorkommt, sei es, dass sie im Exil leben und die Sprache des Exillandes bevorzugen."@de ,
		"Onder Arabische literatuur kan literatuur in het Arabisch worden verstaan, of in bredere zin literaire werken geschreven door Arabische schrijvers in om het even welke taal, bijvoorbeeld als deze schrijvers in ballingschap leefden.De eerste Arabische literatuur verscheen in de 5e eeuw na Christus. 		"La litt\\u00E9rature arabe concerne tous les \\u00E9crits (en prose ou en vers) r\\u00E9dig\\u00E9s en langue arabe. Cela ne comprend pas les \\u0153uvres \\u00E9crites avec l\'alphabet arabe utilis\\u00E9 pour transcrire une autre langue, comme le persan ou l\'ourdou. Le terme \'adab (arabe : \\u0623\\u062F\\u0628 \\u062C \\u0622\\u062F\\u0627\\u0628), qui signifie aujourd\'hui \\u00AB litt\\u00E9rature \\u00BB en arabe, n\'est utilis\\u00E9 en ce sens que depuis la Nahda (XIXe si\\u00E8cle), quand la litt\\u00E9rature arabe s\'est align\\u00E9e sur les concepts et les genres litt\\u00E9raires occidentaux."@fr ,
		"La literatura \\u00E1rabe (en \\u00E1rabe ,\\u0627\\u0644\\u0623\\u062F\\u0628 \\u0627\\u0644\\u0639\\u0631\\u0628\\u064A; Al-Adab Al-Arabi) es el conjunto de textos literarios escritos en lengua \\u00E1rabe; no es habitual, por tanto, incluir las obras que est\\u00E1n escritas usando el alfabeto \\u00E1rabe pero no el idioma, como es el caso de la literatura persa y de la literatura en lengua urdu. La palabra \\u00E1rabe usada para literatura es adab, que deriva de una palabra que significa \\"invitar a alguien a comer\\" y que implica matices de cortes\\u00EDa, cultura y enriquecimiento personal."@es ,
		"Con il termine letteratura araba, si indica l\\u2019insieme di quelle attivit\\u00E0 indirizzate alla produzione di testi scritti, poetici e in prosa, proprie delle popolazioni che hanno fatto uso nello scritto della lingua araba (della famiglia delle lingue semitiche). Pertanto fanno parte della letteratura araba tutti i testi che, a partire dal VI secolo d.C., sono stati composti e scritti in arabo anche da autori che Arabi non erano."@it ,

		"Beaux-Arts architecture (/\\u02CCbo\\u028A\\u02C8z\\u0251r/; French: [boza\\u0281]) expresses the academic neoclassical architectural style taught at the \\u00C9cole des Beaux-Arts in Paris. The style \\"Beaux Arts\\" is above all the cumulative product of two-and-a-half centuries of instruction under the authority, first, of the Acad\\u00E9mie royale d\'architecture (1671\\u20131793), then, following the French Revolution of the late 18th century, of the Architecture section of the Acad\\u00E9mie des Beaux-Arts (1795\\u2013 )."@en ,
		"Beaux-Arts is een ontwerp- en stijlstroming uit het eind van de 19e eeuw en het begin van de 20e eeuw die aansluit bij het neoclassicisme, de neo-barok en de neorenaissance. De stijl is ontstaan in Frankrijk, voorafgaand aan het belle \\u00E9poque."@nl ,
		"Beaux-Arts-Architektur bezeichnet die Architektur des Historismus, wie sie im 19. Jahrhundert von der \\u00C9cole des Beaux-Arts in Paris vertreten wurde. Ihre Architekten errichteten insbesondere zwischen 1850 und 1914 zahlreiche repr\\u00E4sentative Geb\\u00E4ude dieser Stilrichtung vor allem in Frankreich sowie sehr umfangreich auch in den Vereinigten Staaten, Kanada und Australien."@de ,

	rdfs:comment	"Als Afro-Kanadier (amerik.-engl. African Canadian oder Black Canadian) werden alle Einwohner Kanadas bezeichnet, die zumindest teilweise schwarzafrikanischer Abstammung sind. Die Mehrheit der schwarzen Kanadier sind Nachfahren der im 19. Jahrhundert aus den USA gefl\\u00FCchteten Sklaven. Andere Angeh\\u00F6rige dieser Minderheit immigrierten im 20. Jahrhundert aus der Karibik und Afrika ins Land. Im Jahre 2006 waren 2,5 % aller Kanadier Schwarze (783.795 Personen)."@de ,
		"Les Noirs canadiens ou Afro-Canadiens sont les citoyens ou r\\u00E9sidents permanents du Canada ayant des anc\\u00EAtres originaires d\\u2019Afrique noire. La majorit\\u00E9 des Noirs canadiens ont des origines des Cara\\u00EFbes et antillaises. Le terme \\u00AB afro-canadiens \\u00BB, ne faisant pas de distinction entre les origines africaines, afro-carib\\u00E9ennes ou autres, est parfois rejet\\u00E9 par les Canadiens reconnaissant leurs origines plus sp\\u00E9cifiques comme une partie int\\u00E9grale de leur h\\u00E9ritage."@fr ,
		"Black Canadian is a designation used for people of Black African descent, who are citizens or permanent residents of Canada. The term specifically refers to Canadians with partial or direct Sub-Saharan African ancestry. The majority of Black Canadians are of Caribbean origin.Black Canadians and other Canadians often draw a distinction between those of Afro-Caribbean ancestry and those of other African roots."@en .

		"The emerging church is a Christian movement of the late 20th and early 21st centuries that crosses a number of theological boundaries: participants are described as Protestant, post-Protestant, evangelical, post-evangelical, liberal, post-liberal,  conservative, post-conservative, anabaptist, adventist, reformed, charismatic, neocharismatic, and post-charismatic."@en ,
		"Die Emerging Church (auch \\u201EEmerging Conversation\\u201C und \\u201EEmerging Churches\\u201C) ist eine dezentrale, stark heterogene Bewegung von verschiedenen Christen, die in ihrem Umfeld und in ihrer jeweiligen Tradition auf die Herausforderungen der Postmoderne reagieren wollen. 		"De emerging church movement is een christelijke beweging die eind 20e eeuw is opgekomen. De term is een overkoepelend begrip voor een grote diversiteit aan nieuwe, dikwijls experimentele, vormen van (missionair) kerk-zijn in een postmoderne cultuur. De beweging is sterk geori\\u00EBnteerd op de westerse wereld. De term emerging church wordt als onvertaalbaar gezien; letterlijk betekent het \\u201Copkomende kerk\\u201D."@nl ,
		"La iglesia emergente (tambi\\u00E9n conocido como movimiento de la iglesia emergente) es un movimiento cristiano protestante cuyos participantes buscan vivir su fe en la sociedad posmoderna emulando a Jes\\u00FAs de Nazaret independientemente de las tradiciones religiosas cristianas. Los proponentes de este movimiento lo denominan \\"una conversaci\\u00F3n\\" para enfatizar su car\\u00E1cter descentralizado y en pleno desarrollo, as\\u00ED como su \\u00E9nfasis en el di\\u00E1logo intrareligioso en lugar de un evangelismo de una sola v\\u00EDa."@es ,
		"L\'\\u00C9glise \\u00E9mergente est un courant r\\u00E9formiste au sein du christianisme \\u00E9vang\\u00E9lique qui pr\\u00F4ne une r\\u00E9interpr\\u00E9tation des textes sacr\\u00E9s et des pratiques eccl\\u00E9siales selon les principes du postmodernisme."@fr ,
		"Emerging Church \\u2013 kontrowersyjny ruch chrze\\u015Bcija\\u0144ski wywodz\\u0105cy si\\u0119 z protestantyzmu, kieruj\\u0105cy sw\\u0105 dzia\\u0142alno\\u015B\\u0107 ku ludziom niewierz\\u0105cym oraz tym, kt\\u00F3rzy odeszli z ko\\u015Bcio\\u0142\\u00F3w lub zostali z nich wykluczeni."@pl .

		"O KUCHIPUDI surgiu na Vila de Kuchelapuram no estado de Andra Pradesh, no sul da \\u00CDndia. Este estilo consolidou-se no s\\u00E9culo XVII, com o advento do movimento Bhakti, sob o comando de Siddhendra Yogi. Inicialmente, era executado somente por homens em apresenta\\u00E7\\u00F5es coletivas de car\\u00E1ter teatral. Apenas no s\\u00E9c. XX passou a ser praticado por mulheres e aproximou-se do universo das dan\\u00E7as dram\\u00E1ticas indianas."@pt ,
		"Le kuchipudi est une danse indienne, n\\u00E9e dans le village de Kuchipudi dans l\'\\u00C9tat de l\'Andhra Pradesh (sud de l\'Inde). Comme la plupart des danses classiques indiennes, il se jouait dans les temples et en groupe. Autrefois cette danse \\u00E9tait r\\u00E9serv\\u00E9e aux brahmanes qui tenaient aussi les r\\u00F4les f\\u00E9minins. Aujourd\'hui, le kuchipudi peut \\u00EAtre dans\\u00E9 par les femmes et m\\u00EAme en solo."@fr ,

		"Language poets"@it ;
	rdfs:comment	"I Language poets (o L=A=N=G=U=A=G=E poets secondo la rivista dello stesso nome) sono un gruppo o una tendenza avanguardistica nella poesia degli Stati Uniti esistito dalla fine degli anni \'60 e primi anni \'70. La loro poesia enfatizza il ruolo del lettore, cercando di coinvolgerlo nella costruzione del significato del testo, e minimizza l\'importanza della espressione personale del poeta."@it ,
		"Los Poetas del Lenguaje (o  \\"L=A=N=G=U=A=G=E poets\\" , por la revista del mismo nombre) son un grupo o tendencia vanguardista en la poes\\u00EDa de Estados Unidos que surgi\\u00F3 entre finales de los a\\u00F1os 60 y principios de los 70. Para desarrollar su po\\u00E9tica, los miembros de la escuela del Lenguaje tomaron como punto de inicio el enf\\u00E1sis en el m\\u00E9todo evidente en la tradici\\u00F3n modernista, especialmente en la representada por Gertrude Stein y Louis Zukofsky."@es ,
		"The Language poets (or L=A=N=G=U=A=G=E poets, after the magazine of that name) are an avant garde group or tendency in United States poetry that emerged in the late 1960s and early 1970s. The poets included: Leslie Scalapino, Stephen Rodefer."@en ,
		"Die Language poets (oder L=A=N=G=U=A=G=E poets nach der Zeitschrift dieses Namens) sind eine US-amerikanische literarische Gruppe, die sich in den 1960er und 1970er Jahren formierte. Nach eigenem Verst\\u00E4ndnis betont die Language Poetry die Rolle des Lesers bei der Auffassung der Bedeutung eines Textes. Auf Form und Ausdrucksweise wird weniger Wert gelegt, und das Gedicht als Konstrukt in der Sprache und Konstruktion von Sprache angesehen."@de ,
		"Poesia language \\u00E9 uma denomina\\u00E7\\u00E3o gen\\u00E9rica dada ao resultado da experi\\u00EAncia de poetas que aderiram a uma tend\\u00EAncia ou escola est\\u00E9tica da poesia dos Estados Unidos, chamados Language poets, iniciada no final dos anos de 1960 e come\\u00E7o dos anos 1970, e que se desenvolveu em v\\u00E1rias ondas, em mais de uma gera\\u00E7\\u00E3o. Surge como resposta \\u00E0 tradicional poesia daquele pa\\u00EDs e \\u00E0s suas formas."@pt .

		"New Criticism bezeichnet eine vor allem in den USA, in geringerem Ma\\u00DFe auch in England beheimatete literaturkritische und -theoretische Richtung. Sie entwickelte sich in den 1920er Jahren und war in den USA bis in die 1970er Jahre die bestimmende Art der Literaturbetrachtung. Seinen Namen erhielt der New Criticism nach der Anthologie The New Critics, die 1941 von John Crowe Ransom herausgegeben wurde.Der New Criticism richtete sich gegen die seit dem 19."@de ,
		"New Criticism \\u00E8 una corrente letteraria critico-poetica che si \\u00E8 sviluppa negli USA e in Inghilterra fra gli anni trenta e gli anni cinquanta nel segno del rifiuto di ogni spiegazione storico-ideologica della poesia. Il movimento deve il suo nome al volume di John Crowe Ransom The New Criticism (La nuova critica, 1939) e nasce in opposizione alla rigida ortodossia della critica marxista e al moralismo del neoumanesimo."@it ,
		"\\u30CB\\u30E5\\u30FC\\u30FB\\u30AF\\u30EA\\u30C6\\u30A3\\u30B7\\u30BA\\u30E0\\uFF08New ,
		"New Criticism was a formalist movement in literary theory that dominated American literary criticism in the middle decades of the 20th century. It emphasized close reading, particularly of poetry, to discover how a work of literature functioned as a self-contained, self-referential aesthetic object. The movement derived its name from John Crowe Ransom\'s 1941 book The New Criticism."@en .

	rdfs:comment	"De Niagara Movement was een in 1905 opgerichte groep van 32 Afrikaans-Amerikaanse mannen, die streefden naar gelijkheid tussen de blanke en zwarten in de Verenigde Staten van Amerika. De groep was het oneens met de compromissen die Booker T. Washington had gedaan in diens Atlanta Compromise in 1895."@nl ,
		"Die Niagara-Bewegung (engl.: Niagara Movement) wurde 1905 gegr\\u00FCndet, als sich eine Gruppe von 32 afroamerikanischen M\\u00E4nnern unter der Leitung von W. E. B. Du Bois, John Hope und William Monroe Trotter traf, um volle b\\u00FCrgerliche Freiheiten, ein Ende der rassistischen Diskriminierung (Segregation) und volle \\u201EAnerkennung der Bande, die alle Menschen verbinden\\u201C, zu verlangen.Zu den Gr\\u00FCndern der Bewegung geh\\u00F6rten: (Niagara Movement Founders, 1905) H. A. Thompson, Alonzo F."@de ,
		"Le Niagara Movement \\u00E9tait une organisation afro-am\\u00E9ricaine cr\\u00E9\\u00E9e en juillet 1905 \\u00E0 l\'initiative de W. E. B. Du Bois et Monroe Trotter pour r\\u00E9clamer l\'\\u00E9galit\\u00E9 des droits entre Blancs et Noirs."@fr ,
		"El Movimiento del Niagara fue una organizaci\\u00F3n de derechos civiles para negros fundada en 1905 por un grupo liderado por W. E. B. Du Bois y William Monroe Trotter. Fue nombrado as\\u00ED por la \\"poderosa corriente\\" de cambio que el grupo quer\\u00EDa llevar a cabo y por las Cataratas del Ni\\u00E1gara en Canad\\u00E1, donde tuvo lugar su primera reuni\\u00F3n en julio de 1905."@es ,
		"The Niagara Movement   was a black civil rights organization founded in 1905 by a group led by W. E. B. Du Bois and William Monroe Trotter. It was named for the \\"mighty current\\" of change the group wanted to effect and Niagara Falls, near Fort Erie, Ontario, was where the first meeting took place in July 1905."@en .

		"Poesia visual pretende ser um tipo de poesia em que, abolindo-se certas distin\\u00E7\\u00F5es entre os g\\u00EAneros como poesia, teatro, m\\u00FAsica, dan\\u00E7a, pintura, escultura e outros, o texto, as imagens e os s\\u00EDmbolos est\\u00E3o distribu\\u00EDdos de forma que o elemento visual pode assumir a principal fun\\u00E7\\u00E3o organizacional da obra, n\\u00E3o dependendo da exist\\u00EAncia de s\\u00EDmbolos de escrita para sua caracteriza\\u00E7\\u00E3o como poesia, embora n\\u00E3o os excluindo."@pt ,
		"La poes\\u00EDa visual es una forma experimental en la que la imagen, el elemento pl\\u00E1stico, en todas sus facetas, t\\u00E9cnicas y soportes, predomina sobre el resto de los componentes."@es ,
		"La poesia visiva, nasce da tutte quelle sperimentazioni artistiche e letterarie compiute nel clima della Neoavanguardia, a partire dagli anni sessanta del XX secolo.Anche se, tuttavia, \\u00E8 dalla rinascita culturale del secondo dopoguerra che le ricerche verbo-visive hanno il loro punto di partenza, come presa di posizione critica sulla cultura, sulla societ\\u00E0 e sul linguaggio attraverso il quale si esprime la nuova realt\\u00E0 modernizzata e industrializzata del secondo dopoguerra."@it ,
		"La po\\u00E9sie visuelle se distingue de la po\\u00E9sie graphique ou typographique en ce sens o\\u00F9 elle utilise le po\\u00E8me comme forme.Elle prend v\\u00E9ritablement naissance avec les calligrammes de Guillaume Apollinaire de 1918 et rebondit notamment avec le Spatialisme de Pierre Garnier.Mais le po\\u00E8me visuel peut aussi quitter le po\\u00E8me et devenir uniquement un acte visuel."@fr ,
		"Visuelle Poesie ist ein Sammelbegriff f\\u00FCr alle Arten von Poesie oder Dichtung, bei denen die visuelle Pr\\u00E4sentation eines Textes ein wesentliches Element der k\\u00FCnstlerischen Konzeption darstellt. Visuelle Poesie ist abzugrenzen gegen Kalligraphie und typographische Kunstformen, in denen eine neue visuelle Form f\\u00FCr bereits existierende Texte gefunden wird."@de ,
		"Visual poetry is poetry or art in which the visual arrangement of text, images and symbols is important in conveying the intended effect of the work. Confusingly, it is sometimes referred to as concrete poetry, a term that predates visual poetry.Some traditions of visual poetry were heavily influenced by Fluxus, which is usually described as being Intermedia. Intermedia work tends to blur the distinctions between different media, and visual poetry blurs the distinction between art and text."@en .

		"Monochromatic painting has been an important component of avant-garde visual art throughout the 20th century and into the 21st century. Painters have created the exploration of one color, the examination of values changing across a surface, the expressivity of texture and nuance, expressing a wide variety of emotions, intentions and meanings in a wide variety of ways and means. From geometric precision to expressionism, the monochrome has proved to be a durable idiom in Contemporary art."@en .

The term \\"New Woman\\" was coined by writer Sarah Grand in her article \\"The New Aspect of the Woman Question,\\" published in the North American Review in March 1894."@en ,

		"La Nueva Mujer (en ingl\\u00E9s, New Woman) era un ideal feminista que surgi\\u00F3 a finales del siglo XIX. Una nueva mujer que empujaba los l\\u00EDmites establecidos por la sociedad dominada por los hombres, especialmente tal como aparec\\u00EDa en las obras del noruego Henrik Ibsen (1828 - 1906)."@es ,
		"A Nova Mulher (em ingl\\u00EAs: New Woman) foi um ideal feminista que surgiu no final do s\\u00E9culo XIX, que influenciou profundamente o feminismo do s\\u00E9culo XX. O termo \\"nova mulher\\" foi inventado pela escritora irlandesa Sarah Grand em sua obra \\"The New Aspect of the Woman Question,\\" publicada na revista liter\\u00E1ria norte-americana North American Review em mar\\u00E7o de 1894."@pt ,
		"Die Neue Frau war ein feministisches Ideal des sp\\u00E4ten 19. Jahrhunderts. Die von M\\u00E4nnern dominierte Gesellschaft wurde dadurch an ihre Grenzen gebracht, insbesondere durch die St\\u00FCcke des norwegischen Schriftstellers Henrik Ibsen. Max Beerbohm sagte dazu scherzhaft: Vorlage:\\", zu deutsch: Vorlage:\\". Die Neuen Frauen waren vor allem in der Suffragette-Bewegung aktiv, erfuhren aber in den 1920er Jahren durch das Aufkommen der frivolen Flapper einen Bedeutungsverlust."@de .

	rdfs:comment	"El Spoken word (traducido literalmente, significa palabra hablada) es un tipo de performance po\\u00E9tica que utiliza adem\\u00E1s elementos musicales y teatrales. Se centra generalmente en la representaci\\u00F3n de la palabra como tal, el tono, la entonaci\\u00F3n, el ritmo, los gestos y la expresi\\u00F3n facial, entre otros. Mezcla el discurso narrativo con la improvisaci\\u00F3n y recursos po\\u00E9ticos como la rima, los juegos de palabras, las repeticiones etc. para envolver al auditorio en una atm\\u00F3sfera especial."@es ,

		"Spoken word (em tradu\\u00E7\\u00E3o livre: palavra falada) \\u00E9 uma forma de arte liter\\u00E1ria ou uma performance art\\u00EDstica em que as letras de m\\u00FAsicas, os poemas ou as hist\\u00F3rias s\\u00E3o faladas ao inv\\u00E9s de cantadas. O \\"Spoken word\\" \\u00E9, geralmente, feito tamb\\u00E9m no fundo de m\\u00FAsicas, mas a \\u00EAnfase \\u00E9 mantida na pessoa que fala. O \\"spoken word\\" est\\u00E1 no limite entre g\\u00EAneros art\\u00EDsticos."@pt ,
		"Spoken word (lett.: gesproken woord) is voordracht van literatuur, veelal binnen de popcultuur. De voordrachten vinden plaats als lezing of performance, met songteksten, po\\u00EBzie, prozagedichten, proza, kort verhaal, columns, statements, slamgedichten, enzovoorts."@nl ,
		"Spoken word involves performance-based poetry that focuses on the aesthetics of word play and story-telling, that originated from the poetry of African Americans in Harlem. It often includes collaboration and experimentation with other art forms such as music, theater, and dance. There is no mandatory manner in which to perform spoken word, however, certain aspects of the artistry indicate that it is, indeed, spoken word."@en ,

\\u3067\\u55A7\\u5629\\u8170\\u306B\\u8EAB\\u69CB\\u3048\\u308B\\u3001\\u30DD\\u30A8\\u30C8\\u30EA\\u30FC\\u30FB\\u30B9\\u30E9\\u30E0\\u304C\\u51FA\\u73FE\\u3057\\u305F\\u6642\\u306F\\u60AA\\u8A55\\u3092\\u5F97\\u305F\\u3002"@ja ,
		"Le spoken word (litt\\u00E9ralement ) est une fa\\u00E7on particuli\\u00E8re d\'oraliser un texte, qu\'il soit po\\u00E9tique ou autre. Il comprend souvent une collaboration (ou exp\\u00E9rimentation) avec d\'autres formes d\'art comme la musique, le th\\u00E9\\u00E2tre ou la danse. Cependant, le spoken word se concentre essentiellement sur les mots eux-m\\u00EAmes, la dynamique et le ton de la voix, les gestes, les expressions."@fr ,
		"Lo spoken word (dall\'inglese \\"parola parlata\\") \\u00E8 una forma di poesia incentrata sull\'uso delle parole tramite modalit\\u00E0 espressive che spaziano dalla narrazione, alla recitazione e all\'improvvisazione. A volte viene espresso tramite performance multimediali che includono musica e danza.Fra i numerosi artisti che si sono cimentati in questa forma artistica vi sono Gil Scott-Heron, L\\u00E9o Ferr\\u00E9 e Spalding Gray."@it ,

		"O City Beautiful Movement (em portugu\\u00EAs: Movimento da Cidade Bonita) foi uma reforma arquitet\\u00F4nica americana surgida entre 1890 e 1900 com a inten\\u00E7\\u00E3o de revitalizar e tornar mais emblem\\u00E1ticos os espa\\u00E7os p\\u00FAblicos das cidades americanas. O movimento floresceu em Chicago, Detroit e Washington, D.C. e mais tarde se espalhou por outros estados norte-americanos."@pt ,
		"De City Beautiful-beweging  was een hervormingsfilosofie binnen de Noord-Amerikaanse architectuur en stedenbouwkunde in de jaren 1890 en 1900. De beweging stond voor de verfraaiing van de stad en voor monumentale grandeur. Ze streefden niet uitsluitend schoonheid na als doel op zich, maar ook om aan te zetten tot deugdzaamheid in de steden. De nieuwe architectuur zou op die manier bijdragen tot een harmonieuze maatschappij met een hogere levenskwaliteit."@nl ,
		"\\u90FD\\u5E02\\u7F8E\\u904B\\u52D5\\uFF08\\u3068\\u3057\\u3073\\u3046\\u3093\\u3069\\u3046\\u3001\\u82F1\\u8A9E\\uFF1ACity Beautiful movement\\uFF09\\u306F\\u3001\\u5317\\u30A2\\u30E1\\u30EA\\u30AB\\u3067\\u6804\\u3048\\u305F\\u90FD\\u5E02\\u8A08\\u753B\\u306E\\u9769\\u65B0\\u904B\\u52D5\\u3002"@ja ,
		"The City Beautiful Movement was a reform philosophy of North American architecture and urban planning that flourished during the 1890s and 1900s with the intent of introducing beautification and monumental grandeur in cities. The movement, which was originally associated mainly with Chicago, Cleveland, Detroit, and Washington, D.C., promoted beauty not only for its own sake, but also to create moral and civic virtue among urban populations."@en ,
		"Le City Beautiful est un mouvement architectural et urbanistique qui se d\\u00E9veloppa dans les ann\\u00E9es 1890 et 1900 aux \\u00C9tats-Unis, \\u00E0 Chicago et D\\u00E9troit en particulier. La recherche de la beaut\\u00E9 dans une finalit\\u00E9 sociale et civique anime cette tendance."@fr ,

El movimiento floreci\\u00F3 en Chicago, Detroit y Washington, D.C. y m\\u00E1s tarde se expandi\\u00F3 por otros estados norte-americanos."@es ,

		"Il Nuovo giornalismo (dall\'inglese New Journalism) \\u00E8 uno stile anticonvenzionale di giornalismo degli anni sessanta e settanta."@it ,
		"New Journalism is a style of news writing and journalism, developed in the 1960s & \'70s, which used literary techniques deemed unconventional at the time. It is characterized by a subjective perspective, a literary style reminiscent of long-form non-fiction and emphasizing \\"truth\\" over \\"facts,\\" and intensive reportage in which reporters immersed themselves in the stories as they reported and wrote them."@en ,
		"Le Nouveau journalisme (en anglais New Journalism) est un style de journalisme faisant appel \\u00E0 certaines techniques litt\\u00E9raires, adopt\\u00E9 principalement dans la presse \\u00E9crite des ann\\u00E9es 1960 et 1970. L\'expression fut utilis\\u00E9e pour la premi\\u00E8re fois par Tom Wolfe en 1973, dans une anthologie d\'articles publi\\u00E9e sous le titre de The New Journalism et r\\u00E9unissant des articles de lui-m\\u00EAme, mais aussi de Truman Capote, Hunter S. Thompson, Norman Mailer, Robert Christgau, Barbara Goldsmith, Herbert R."@fr ,
		"Nowe Dziennikarstwo (New Journalism) opiera si\\u0119 na stosowaniu literackich technik w reporta\\u017Cach i esejach, co nadaje tekstom walor ekspresjonistyczny, zwany ostatnio \\"histerycznym\\". Nazw\\u0119 uku\\u0142 Tom Wolfe, wydaj\\u0105c w 1973 roku zbi\\u00F3r artyku\\u0142\\u00F3w r\\u00F3\\u017Cnych autor\\u00F3w pod tytu\\u0142em The New Journalism.G\\u0142\\u00F3wni przedstawiciele: Tom Wolfe, Joan Didion, Truman Capote (Z zimn\\u0105 krwi\\u0105), Hunter S."@pl ,

		"Unter dem Begriff New Journalism (deutsch: \\u201ANeuer Journalismus\\u2019) wird ein Schreib- und Reportagestil verstanden, der in den 1960er und 1970er Jahren in den USA aufkam. Er wich von der sonst \\u00FCblichen journalistischen Praxis insofern ab, als dass er h\\u00F6chst subjektiv vorging, verst\\u00E4rkt auf literarische Stilmittel zur\\u00FCckgriff und sich dabei dennoch an die Fakten hielt.Die gewohnte Grenzziehung zwischen Literatur und Journalismus wurde verschoben."@de ,

dbr:War_poet	rdfs:label	"War poet"@en ;
	rdfs:comment	"A war poet is usually defined as a poet who participates in a war and writes about his experiences. While the term is applied especially to those who served during World War I, it is documented as early as 1848, in reference to German revolutionary poet, Georg Herwegh. and is now applied to a poet writing about any war. However, Tennyson wrote probably one of the most famous war poems of the nineteenth century, and another non-combatant, Thomas Hardy, wrote major war poetry."@en .

dbr:Francisco_de_Zurbar\xc3\xa1n	dbo:movement	dbr:Caravaggisti .
<http://dbpedia.org/resource/Fugitives_(poets)>	rdfs:label	"Fugitives (poets)"@en ,
		"I Fuggiaschi"@it ;
	rdfs:comment	"I Fuggiaschi (The Fugitives in lingua inglese) \\u00E8 stato un movimento letterario di poeti e letterati che si riunivano alla Vanderbilt University a Nashville, Tennessee negli anni venti. Il movimento prese il nome da The Fugitive (Il Fuggiasco) un piccolo mensile letterario pubblicato a Nashville tra il 1922 e il 1925 nel quale apparvero i loro lavori. Anche se la pubblicazione ebbe vita breve, The Fugitive \\u00E8 ritenuta una delle riviste pi\\u00F9 influenti nella storia della letteratura americana."@it ,
		"The Fugitives were a group of poets and literary scholars who came together at Vanderbilt University in Nashville, Tennessee, around 1920. They acquired the name after publishing a small literary magazine, The Fugitive, from 1922-1925 which showcased their works.  Although its publication history was brief, The Fugitive is considered to be one of the most influential journals in the history of American letters."@en .

		"Narratology refers to both the theory and the study of narrative and narrative structure and the ways that these affect our perception. While in principle the word may refer to any systematic study of narrative, in practice its usage is rather more restricted. It is an anglicisation of French narratologie, coined by Tzvetan Todorov (Grammaire du D\\u00E9cam\\u00E9ron, 1969). Narratology is applied retrospectively as well to work predating its coinage."@en ,
		"\\u041D\\u0430\\u0440\\u0440\\u0430\\u0442\\u043E\\u043B\\u043E\\u0433\\u0438\\u044F, \\u0442\\u0435\\u043E\\u0440\\u0438\\u044F \\u043D\\u0430\\u0440\\u0440\\u0430\\u0442\\u0438\\u0432\\u0430, \\u0442\\u0435\\u043E\\u0440\\u0438\\u044F \\u043F\\u043E\\u0432\\u0435\\u0441\\u0442\\u0432\\u043E\\u0432\\u0430\\u043D\\u0438\\u044F \\u2014 \\u043D\\u0430\\u0443\\u0447\\u043D\\u0430\\u044F \\u0434\\u0438\\u0441\\u0446\\u0438\\u043F\\u043B\\u0438\\u043D\\u0430, \\u0438\\u0437\\u0443\\u0447\\u0430\\u044E\\u0449\\u0430\\u044F \\u043F\\u043E\\u0432\\u0435\\u0441\\u0442\\u0432\\u043E\\u0432\\u0430\\u043D\\u0438\\u0435 \\u0432 \\u0446\\u0435\\u043B\\u043E\\u043C. \\u041D\\u0430\\u0440\\u0440\\u0430\\u0442\\u043E\\u043B\\u043E\\u0433\\u0438\\u044F \\u0441\\u0442\\u0430\\u0432\\u0438\\u0442 \\u043F\\u0435\\u0440\\u0435\\u0434 \\u0441\\u043E\\u0431\\u043E\\u0439 \\u0437\\u0430\\u0434\\u0430\\u0447\\u0438 \\u0432\\u044B\\u044F\\u0432\\u043B\\u0435\\u043D\\u0438\\u044F \\u043E\\u0431\\u0449\\u0438\\u0445 \\u0447\\u0435\\u0440\\u0442 \\u0440\\u0430\\u0437\\u043B\\u0438\\u0447\\u043D\\u044B\\u0445 \\u043D\\u0430\\u0440\\u0440\\u0430\\u0442\\u0438\\u0432\\u043E\\u0432, \\u043E\\u043F\\u0440\\u0435\\u0434\\u0435\\u043B\\u0435\\u043D\\u0438\\u044F \\u0440\\u0430\\u0437\\u043B\\u0438\\u0447\\u0438\\u0439 \\u043C\\u0435\\u0436\\u0434\\u0443 \\u043D\\u0438\\u043C\\u0438, \\u0441\\u0438\\u0441\\u0442\\u0435\\u043C\\u0430\\u0442\\u0438\\u0437\\u0430\\u0446\\u0438\\u0438 \\u0437\\u0430\\u043A\\u043E\\u043D\\u043E\\u0432 \\u0441\\u043E\\u0437\\u0434\\u0430\\u043D\\u0438\\u044F \\u0438 \\u0440\\u0430\\u0437\\u0432\\u0438\\u0442\\u0438\\u044F \\u043D\\u0430\\u0440\\u0440\\u0430\\u0442\\u0438\\u0432\\u043E\\u0432."@ru ,
		"La narratologie (science de la narration) est la discipline qui \\u00E9tudie les techniques et les structures narratives mises en \\u0153uvre dans les textes litt\\u00E9raires (ou d\'autres formes de r\\u00E9cit).Les premiers travaux en narratologie des \\u00E9tudes litt\\u00E9raires modernes proviennent du formalisme russe et tout particuli\\u00E8rement des travaux de Victor Chklovski et de Boris Eichenbaum.L\'\\u00E9tude syst\\u00E9matique de la morphologie des contes russes par Vladimir Propp connait une bonne diffusion en France, parall\\u00E8lement aux travaux (en particulier le sch\\u00E9ma actantiel) d\'Algirdas Julien Greimas. "@fr ,
		"De narratologie is een tekstbenadering in de literaire kritiek en in de antropologie, die het vertellen (of de vertelwijze) van verhalen als haar studieobject kiest. De narratologie in wijde zin omvat zowel de verhaaltheorie als de verteltheorie. Deze houden zich bezig met verhalen. Een verhaal is een eenheid en samenhang vertonende geschiedenis (een reeks van met elkaar logisch en chronologisch verbonden gebeurtenissen), die door een verteller gepresenteerd wordt."@nl ,
		"La narratolog\\u00EDa es la disciplina semi\\u00F3tica a la que compete el estudio estructural de los relatos, as\\u00ED como su comunicaci\\u00F3n y recepci\\u00F3n.Aunque tiene una larga tradici\\u00F3n anterior, los mayores avances en el campo de la narratolog\\u00EDa se deben al estructuralismo, que subdividi\\u00F3 y clasific\\u00F3 los rasgos principales de toda narraci\\u00F3n."@es ,
		"Die Erz\\u00E4hltheorie oder Erz\\u00E4hlforschung ist eine interdisziplin\\u00E4re Methode der Geisteswissenschaften, Kulturwissenschaften und Sozialwissenschaften, die eine systematische Beschreibung der Darstellungsform eines Erz\\u00E4hltextes anstrebt. Die englische Bezeichnung lautet \\u201Enarratology\\u201C, die franz\\u00F6sische \\u201Enarratologie\\u201C. Deshalb taucht auch im Deutschen der Begriff Narratologie auf."@de ,
		"Il termine narratologia fu coniato dal filosofo Tzvetan Todorov (nel 1969) per indicare lo studio delle strutture narrative. Angelo Marchese, nel 1983 scriveva:\\"La narratologia \\u00E8 una disciplina ancora in fieri..."@it ,
		"A Narratologia \\u00E9 o estudo das narrativas de fic\\u00E7\\u00E3o e n\\u00E3o-fic\\u00E7\\u00E3o (como a Hist\\u00F3ria e a reportagem), por meio de suas estruturas e elementos. \\u00C9 um campo de estudos particularmente \\u00FAtil para a dramaturgia e o roteiro de audiovisual (cinema, quadrinhos e TV). A narratologia foi consolidada como ci\\u00EAncia por pesquisadores franceses (como Roland Barthes) e pela chamada Escola Formalista Russa, de A.J. Greimas, Vladimir Propp e outros."@pt .

		"El posmodernista surge en el periodo inmediatamente posterior a la Segunda Guerra Mundial (despu\\u00E9s de 1945), siendo su m\\u00E1xime el intento de superar el proyecto modernista, proyecto que fracas\\u00F3 en su intento por renovar de una forma radical las formas del arte establecidas hasta aquel momento, es decir, las formas tradicionales o formales.En cuanto al posmodernismo literario, y aun siendo una disciplina dif\\u00EDcilmente definible, es al mismo tiempo una negaci\\u00F3n y una afirmaci\\u00F3n del paradigma modernista. "@es ,
		"Voir aussi postmodernisme, Postmodernisme (architecture), postmodernit\\u00E9 et philosophie postmoderne.La litt\\u00E9rature postmoderne prend ses distances avec le projet moderniste. Elle rel\\u00E8ve du \\u00AB petit r\\u00E9cit \\u00BB chez Jean-Fran\\u00E7ois Lyotard, du \\u00AB jeu \\u00BB selon Jacques Derrida  et du \\u00AB simulacre \\u00BB selon Jean Baudrillard.Par exemple, au lieu de la qu\\u00EAte moderniste de sens dans un monde chaotique, l\'auteur post-moderne \\u00E9vite, souvent de mani\\u00E8re ludique, la possibilit\\u00E9 du sens."@fr ,
		"De postmoderne of postmodernistische literatuur is de manifestatie van het postmodernisme in de literatuur. Het gaat om een intellectuele beweging die zich in de tweede helft van de twintigste eeuw vanuit de Verenigde Staten en Frankrijk in de hele westerse wereld verspreidde als een tegenbeweging tegen de literatuuropvattingen van de modernisten.In de VS was de term al in gebruik in de jaren zestig, naast andere zoals \\"the new fiction\\" en \\"sur-fiction\\"."@nl ,
		"La tendenza letteraria che nasce come una serie di stili e idee dopo la seconda guerra mondiale in reazione alle teorizzazioni del modernismo viene chiamato letteratura postmoderna, ed estende molte delle tecniche ed assunzioni fondamentali della stessa letteratura modernista."@it ,

		"Postmodern literature is literature characterized by reliance on narrative techniques such as fragmentation, paradox, and the unreliable narrator; and often is (though not exclusively) defined as a style or a trend which emerged in the post\\u2013World War II era. Postmodern works are seen as a response against Enlightenment thinking and Modernist approaches to literature.Postmodern literature, like postmodernism as a whole, tends to resist definition or classification as a \\"movement\\"."@en ,
		"Postmodernizm \\u2013 pr\\u0105d literacki, kt\\u00F3rego pocz\\u0105tek datuje si\\u0119 na lata 60. XX wieku. Nazwa nurtu nawi\\u0105zuje do s\\u0142owa \\"ponowoczesno\\u015B\\u0107\\" (postmoderna), tzn. okresu, kt\\u00F3ry nast\\u0105pi\\u0142 po modernizmie i wi\\u0105\\u017Ce si\\u0119 \\u015Bci\\u015Ble z filozofi\\u0105 postmodernizmu.W przeciwie\\u0144stwie do modernizmu, pisarze i poeci postmodernistyczni nie sformu\\u0142owali \\u017Cadnego manifestu ani programu literackiego."@pl .

dbr:Social_poetry	rdfs:label	"Social poetry"@en ,
		"Poes\\u00EDa social"@es ;
	rdfs:comment	"Social poetry is a term which has been broadly used to describe poetry which performs a social function or contains a level of social commentary. The term seems to have first appeared as a translation from the original Spanish Poesia Soc\\u00EDal,  used to describe the post-Spanish-civil-war poetry movement of the 1950s and 60s  (including poets such as Blas de Otero ). Later, Jos\\u00E9 Eduardo Lim\\u00F3n, for example, has used it to describe Mexican-American Chicano poetry in Texas during the same period."@en ,
		"Poes\\u00EDa social es un movimiento po\\u00E9tico espa\\u00F1ol de los a\\u00F1os 1950 y 1960 caracterizado por las condiciones pol\\u00EDticas y la reivindicaci\\u00F3n de la libertad."@es .

		"Le droit des peuples autochtones est l\'ensemble des dispositions juridiques internationales visant \\u00E0 prot\\u00E9ger les 370 millions de personnes (ainsi que leurs modes de vie) composant les peuples autochtones.Cette discipline aspire \\u00E0 prot\\u00E9ger leurs modes d\'organisations sociales, \\u00E9conomiques et politiques ainsi que leurs conceptions politiques, sociales, \\u00E9conomiques et culturelles gr\\u00E2ce \\u00E0 un cadre juridique adapt\\u00E9 et mondialement reconnu."@fr ,
		"Os direitos ind\\u00EDgenas s\\u00E3o os direitos coletivos que existem como reconhecimento \\u00E0 condi\\u00E7\\u00E3o dos povos ind\\u00EDgenas. 		"I diritti degli indigeni sono quei diritti che esistono per salvaguardare e tutelare l\'esistenza dei popoli indigeni. Essi non includono solo i pi\\u00F9 elementari diritti umani di sopravvivenza fisica e integrit\\u00E0, ma anche la conservazione della loro terra, la lingua, la religione e gli altri elementi del patrimonio culturale che fanno parte della loro esistenza come popolo."@it ,
		"Los derechos de los ind\\u00EDgenas son aquellos derechos colectivos que existen como reconocimiento a la condici\\u00F3n espec\\u00EDfica de los pueblos aut\\u00F3ctonos. Los mismos incluyen no solo los derechos humanos m\\u00E1s b\\u00E1sicos a la vida e integridad, sino tambi\\u00E9n los derechos sobre su territorio, al idioma, cultura, religi\\u00F3n y otros elementos que forman parte de su identidad como pueblo."@es .

	rdfs:comment	"Light and Space denotes a loosely affiliated art movement related to op art, minimalism and geometric abstraction originating in Southern California in the 1960s and influenced by John McLaughlin. It was characterized by a focus on perceptual phenomena, such as light, volume and scale, and the use of materials such as glass, neon, fluorescent lights, resin and cast acrylic, often forming installations conditioned by the work\'s surroundings."@en .

dbr:Flarf_poetry	rdfs:label	"Flarf poetry"@en ,
		"Flarf"@nl ;
	rdfs:comment	"Flarf poetry is an avant-garde poetry movement of the early 21st century. The term Flarf was coined by the poet Gary Sullivan, who also wrote and published the earliest Flarf poems. Its first practitioners, working in loose collaboration on an email listserv, used an approach that rejected conventional standards of quality and explored subject matter and tonality not typically considered appropriate for poetry."@en ,
		"Een flarf is een gedicht waarin zoekresultaten van het internet zijn verwerkt. Een flarf kan geheel bestaan uit zoekresultaten, maar ook een tekst zijn die ermee is gelardeerd. Flarf is van oorsprong een Amerikaans fenomeen, waar zich tegenwoordig ook enkele dichters in het Nederlandse taalgebied mee bezighouden, en kan worden gezien als een moderne vorm van de readymade of collage."@nl .

	rdfs:comment	"Contimporanul (antiquated spelling of the Romanian word for \\"the Contemporary\\", singular masculine form) was a Romanian (initially a weekly and later a monthly) avant-garde literary and art magazine, published in Bucharest between June 1922 and 1932."@en ,
		"Contimporanul (zu deutsch: Der Zeitgenosse) war eine rum\\u00E4nische K\\u00FCnstlergruppe und Avantgarde-Zeitschrift der 1920er und 1930er Jahre.Die Zeitschrift erschien (mit einigen Unterbrechungen) von 1922 bis 1933; zun\\u00E4chst w\\u00F6chentlich, dann monatlich. Sie gilt als das bedeutendste Organ der rum\\u00E4nischen Avantgarde der ersten H\\u00E4lfte des 20. Jahrhunderts. Die von ihren Herausgebern Marcel Janco und Ion Vinea proklamierte Antib\\u00FCrgerlichkeit verband sich seit 1924 mit dem Konzept des Konstruktivismus."@de .

	rdfs:comment	"Die Soci\\u00E9t\\u00E9 des Vingt, kurz Les XX oder Les Vingt, deutsch Die XX oder Die Zwanzig war eine 1883 oder 1884 (Januar) gegr\\u00FCndete Vereinigung von belgischen oder in Belgien lebenden K\\u00FCnstlern, darunter Fernand Khnopff, Th\\u00E9o van Rysselberghe, James Ensor und das Geschwisterpaar Anna und Eug\\u00E8ne Boch. 		"Les XX was a group of twenty Belgian painters, designers and sculptors, formed in 1883 by the Brussels lawyer, publisher, and entrepreneur Octave Maus. For ten years \\"Les Vingt\\" (French pronunciation: \\u200B[l\\u025B v\\u025B\\u0303]), as they called themselves, held an annual exhibition of their art; each year twenty international artists were also invited to participate in the exhibition."@en ,

Les membres du groupe des XX sont appel\\u00E9s \\u00AB vingtistes \\u00BB."@fr ,

		"Les XX (Les Vingt) was een vernieuwingsgezinde Belgische kunstenaarsgroep van schilders en beeldhouwers, die tussen 1883 en 1893 actief was. Mecenas en animator was de Brusselse jurist Octave Maus, die ook de uitgever was van L\'art moderne, het offici\\u00EBle orgaan van de groep. Zij vormden een groep jonge radicale artiesten die rebelleerden tegen het verouderde academisme en de heersende artistieke standaarden."@nl ,
		"Les XX (pol. Dwudziestu) by\\u0142o to ugrupowanie belgijskich malarzy, projektant\\u00F3w i rze\\u017Abiarzy, za\\u0142o\\u017Cone w 1883 przez brukselskiego prawnika, publicyst\\u0119 i przedsi\\u0119biorc\\u0119 Octave\'a Mausa. Przez dziesi\\u0119\\u0107 lat Les Vingt, jak sami siebie nazywali, organizowali coroczne wystawy swoich dzie\\u0142; do udzia\\u0142u w wystawach zapraszano ponadto dwudziestu artyst\\u00F3w z r\\u00F3\\u017Cnych kraj\\u00F3w. W\\u015Br\\u00F3d zapraszanych artyst\\u00F3w byli: Camille Pissarro, Claude Monet, Georges Seurat, Paul Gauguin, Paul C\\u00E9zanne i Vincent van Gogh."@pl ,
		"Les XX fu un gruppo di venti artisti belgi (pittori, scultori, designer). Nacque a Bruxelles nel 1884, quando, analogamente a ci\\u00F2 che accadeva a Parigi  con il Salon degli Artisti Indipendenti, gli artisti belgi rifiutati dall\'esposizione ufficiale inaugurarono il Salon dei XX.Promotori del nuovo gruppo d\'avanguardia furono Octave Maus e Th\\u00E9o van Rysselberghe."@it ,
		"Los XX (en franc\\u00E9s, Les XX) fue un grupo de veinte pintores belgas, dibujantes y escultores, que se form\\u00F3 en 1883 por el abogado, editor y empresario de Bruselas Octave Maus. Durante diez a\\u00F1os, estos vingtistes, como se llamaban a s\\u00ED mismos, celebraron una exposici\\u00F3n anual de su arte; cada a\\u00F1o se invitaba tambi\\u00E9n a otros veinte artistas internacionales a participar en la exposici\\u00F3n."@es .

		"Internet art (often referred to as net art) is a form of digital artwork distributed via the Internet.  This form of art has circumvented the traditional dominance of the gallery and museum system, delivering aesthetic experiences via the Internet. In many cases, the viewer is drawn into some kind of interaction with the work of art."@en ,
		"\\u041D\\u0435\\u0442-\\u0430\\u0440\\u0442 (\\u0438\\u043B\\u0438 \\u00AB\\u0441\\u0435\\u0442\\u0435\\u0432\\u043E\\u0435 \\u0438\\u0441\\u043A\\u0443\\u0441\\u0441\\u0442\\u0432\\u043E\\u00BB; \\u0430\\u043D\\u0433\\u043B."@ru ,
		"Netzkunst ist ein Sammelbegriff f\\u00FCr k\\u00FCnstlerische Arbeit in Netzen oder Netzwerken. Darunter fallen als Kunstwerk definierte soziale Netze, die k\\u00FCnstlerische Nutzung analoger Netze wie urspr\\u00FCnglich bei Mail Art, sowie k\\u00FCnstlerische Arbeiten, die digitale Netzdienste wie das World Wide Web oder andere Kommunikationsnetze wie Mobilfunk benutzen."@de ,
		"Internetkunst is kunst die speciaal gemaakt is voor het internet."@nl ,
		"Depuis le milieu des ann\\u00E9es 1990, l\'interr\\u00E9seau Internet est un espace actif d\'exp\\u00E9rimentations artistiques. L\'art en ligne utilise ainsi le r\\u00E9seau Internet comme support de diffusion, mais aussi et surtout comme espace de cr\\u00E9ation et d\'existence m\\u00EAme de l\'\\u0153uvre. D\'un point de vue technique, cette forme de pratique artistique implique l\'infrastructure, les langages de programmation et les protocoles de l\'Internet."@fr ,
		"Internet art \\u00E9 a designa\\u00E7\\u00E3o de um movimento global de arte contempor\\u00E2nea a qual \\u00E9 produzida \\"para\\" e \\"pela\\" internet. Depois que a rede mundial de computadores deixou de ser de uso exclusivo dos cientistas e militares, os artistas do ocidente at\\u00E9 os ex-comunistas do leste europeu tornaram-se seus primeiros participantes."@pt .
